  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA61-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaivaṉ varavuṇarntu talaivikkuc colluvāḷāyt tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said as one speaking to HER after realising tht HE would come.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA61">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            kēḷā yella tōḻi yalkal</l>
<l>            vēṇavā naliya veyya vuyirā</l>
<l>            vēmāṉ piṇaiyiṉ varuntiṉe ṉākat</l>
<l>            tuyarmaruṅ kaṟintaṉaḷ pōla vaṉṉai</l>
<l>            tuñcā yōveṉ kuṟumaka ḷeṉṟaliṟ </l>
<l>            colveḷip paṭāmai mellave ṉeñciṟ</l>
<l>            paṭumaḻai poḻinta pāṟai maruṅkiṟ</l>
<l>            ciralvā yuṟṟa taḷaviṟ paralavaṟ</l>
<l>            kāṉkeḻu nāṭaṟ paṭarntōrkkuk</l>
<l>            kaṇṇum paṭumō veṉṟiciṉ yāṉē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Listen, friend, [my] friend:</l>
<l rend="indent3">at night,</l>
<l rend="indent3">as I suffered like the doe of a stag [pierced by] an arrow(?),</l>
<l rend="indent3">sighing hotly while afflicted by increasing desire,</l>
<l rend="indent2">when mother, as if she knew the order(?)<note place="foot">How to understand <term xml:lang="ta">maruṅku</term> here?</note> of [my] misery,</l>
<l rend="indent2">said “don't you sleep, my little daughter?”,</l>
<l rend="indent3">without the words coming out even softly from my heart</l>
<l>I said:</l>
<l rend="indent">“will the eyes close also for</l>
<l rend="indent">those that have been thinking of the man from the forested land,</l>
<l rend="indent2">with pebbly pits of golden jasmine having a kingfisher's beak<note place="foot">Here we can either understand that the jasmine buds are as elongated and thick as the beak of the kingfisher, or that the said beak is what is to be seen of the bird sitting in the branches. There are, however, later passages that support the former interpretation: <term xml:lang="ta">ciral vāy vaṉappiṉ āki ... taḷavam</term> (Kārnāṟpatu 36.1f.).</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">by the side of the rocks overflown by falling rain?”</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
